Use type `char` for letters, not type `int` (which is for integers, or numbers).

Put literal Character values in quotes, otherwise, Java thinks you are referring to variables named `J`, `M` and `F`.

    class Initials {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            char init1;   // char is for letters, int is for Integer/Numbers
            char init2;
            char init3;
            init1 = &#39;J&#39;;  // Single-quote for Literal character values
            init2 = &#39;M&#39;;
            init3 = &#39;F&#39;;
            System.out.println(&quot;Here are your initials &quot; + init1 + init2 + init3);
        }
    }


[IDEOne Link][1] proving it works.

##Output:

    Success #stdin #stdout 0.12s 36572KB
    Here are your initials JMF


&lt;hr&gt;

If you want the period after each one, then use Strings (which are more than one character):

    class Initials {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            String init1;   // String is for a sequence of letters
            String init2;
            String init3;
            init1 = &quot;J.&quot;;  // DoubleQuotes Literal String Values
            init2 = &quot;M.&quot;;
            init3 = &quot;F.&quot;;
            System.out.println(&quot;Here are your initials &quot; + init1 + init2 + init3);
        }
    }

##Output

    Success #stdin #stdout 0.12s 37092KB
    Here are your initials J.M.F.

  [1]: https://ideone.com/IVAFZU

    class Initials {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            String init1 = &quot;J.&quot;;
            String init2 = &quot;M.&quot;;
            String init3 = &quot;F.&quot;;
            System.out.println(&quot;Here are your initials &quot; + init1 + init2 + init3);
        }
    }

You have several options as Java provides many types. The code example above is using the String type, which allows for storing multiple characters. So the initial along with the period can be stored together. Also, one convenient way that String objects can be concatenated is using the &quot;+&quot; operator.

In Java when you declare a variable you need to declare its `type`. 

In your case, you are declaring your variables as `int`, which means you want to put a _whole number_ into it.  For example, you can do `int value = 5;`.

Now if you want to store a single _character_ you can use the type `char` and use single quotes around the value.  This would look like `char value = &#39;J&#39;;`.

A third important type to learn is `String`.  This will allow you store _multiple_ characters in a row, but you need double quotes for the value.  This will look like this `String value = &quot;J.M.F.&quot;;`.

For your scenario, it would make sense to create a single variable as a `String` and display the values together.  Optionally you could also store each individual character as `char` and display them together in the `print`, though this is not recommended unless necessary.  

Before you were attempting to cram _letters_ into a field that only takes _whole numbers_! 

The improved code using `String` would look like this below:

    class Initials {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            String initials = &quot;J.M.F.&quot;;
            System.out.println(&quot;Here are your initials: &quot; + initials);
        }
    }

**Output:**
&gt;Here are your initials: J.M.F.

**Note:**  There are many other types I have not included here, and you can even make your own types!  This is mainly a guide to some of the basic ones you will see.  A few of the other types include `boolean`, `double`, and `long`.

See [here](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/nutsandbolts/datatypes.html) for more details from the documentation on some different types.

