The reason you have to provide your new component in all of your tests is that you declare the real components as dependencies instead of mocking them in each spec file.
Right now at least one of your dependencies depends on your new component, so you must then also declare your new component.

Instead you should have fake components that stand in for your real ones. In your example you are testing the SampleComponent. It should be the only real declaration you have. Everything else should be faked. 

Here is an example of how to fake AccessDeniedComponent

```
@Component({
  selector: &#39;app-access-denied&#39;,
  template: `&lt;div&gt;Access Denied&lt;/div&gt;`,
})
export class FakeAccessDeniedComponent{
  // any public input/outputs the real one has
  // any public method necessary for your tests
}
```

In this case you will want the fake to have the same selector as the real one and the same public inputs/outputs/methods used outside of the file. In your SampleComponent spec you would now declare FakeAccessDeniedComponent instead of the real one.

In your tests themselves they should only expect that you have passed in data to the inputs, called the methods, or listened to the outputs. Any such output event should be faked in test that needs it.

For AOT to work you&#39;ll want to add your fake components to a fake module. That fake module doesn&#39;t need to be imported by anything.

Pretending that you go through all of your dependencies you&#39;ll likely not need to import as many modules, as you only need to import the modules that SampleComponent needs to work. You&#39;ll also likely not need to declare as many components, as you&#39;ll only need what SampleComponent depends on.

